      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-code",
        "dcterms:title": "Holo Code is a substrate-native, sovereign reproduction of the Claude Code terminal agent (apps/code) — the same faithful agentic experience (streaming replies, tool-call blocks, slash commands, plan mode, permission prompts, a content-addressed file/diff viewer), but the brain runs on YOUR machine and nothing is taken on trust. Its whole closure RE-DERIVES to its content address (a single did:holo, Law L5) and is self-contained over the OS runtime (0 fallbacks). The inference brain is a PLUGGABLE provider: a local, deterministic agent turns a request into REAL substrate tool calls (read · write · edit · glob · grep · verify · build · run · share over the holo-files content-addressed VFS, each result carrying the did:holo κ of the bytes it touched) with zero model download — OR the Holo Q (QVAC WebGPU, ADR-0052) on-device LLM, which runs the full desktop-Claude agentic loop: armed with the tool schemas + a coding persona, the model reasons and emits Qwen2.5 function-calls, and the agent executes each tool conscience-gated over the substrate and feeds the result back until it answers (composing Holo Q's own loader→engine + toolSystemPrompt/parseToolCalls wire-format; greedy decode is deterministic, so the turn re-derives — Law L5). Permission is the FAIL-CLOSED conscience gate (ADR-033): the agent evaluates every tool call against the OS Constitution and refuses when unsealed, with the familiar Claude Code modes (default · plan · auto · acceptEdits · bypass) layered on that constitutional floor. Every session seals to a re-derivable PROV-O work receipt (steps · target κ · conscience verdict) — a session you can prove, not just remember. The witness re-derives the shipped bytes AND executes the shipped provider logic (no browser, no server): the local brain demonstrably turns 'read src/greet.js' into a read_file tool call"
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:failed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
