    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-bittensor",
        "dcterms:title": "The live decentralized intelligence market (Bittensor / Subtensor) is projected INTO the substrate's agent fabric as self-verifying UOR objects, NOT bridged as a foreign runtime (ADR-0071) — because a Bittensor subnet IS already a NANDA registry (hotkey → neuron → axon → subnet task = AgentName → record → AgentFacts → endpoint → capability), the projection generalizes Holo NANDA (ADR-034) and is BETTER than a bridge: it re-derives. The metagraph at a block is a κ-rooted dcat:Catalog of neuron AgentFacts whose root did:holo PINS the block hash (so it re-derives against Bittensor's own Merkle chain, Law L5); each neuron is ONE document that is, on the same bytes, a valid NANDA AgentFacts record · a self-verifying UOR object · a W3C VC signed by the neuron's hotkey (dual trust — a vanilla NANDA resolver accepts the signature today, a UOR peer re-derives the address forever), and a did:pkh chain principal in the one κ graph (composing the Chain Abstraction Layer, #chain); tampering ANY byte breaks BOTH the content address and the hotkey signature. Yuma stake/consensus projects into a re-derivable AgentTrust attestation whose auditTrail IS the snapshot κ — a Sybil-resistant, capital-backed reputation oracle the substrate cannot mint, un-gameable because the witness recomputes it. κ ⇆ IPFS CIDv1 (the os-peers law) · the projection is deterministic (build-twice-equal) · mints nothing beyond the published bt: vocabulary. HONEST SCOPE: the Python bt SDK is not run — the chain read is an INGEST BOUNDARY (Subtensor's public, decentralized JSON-RPC, never a server we run; the witness uses a deterministic snapshot fixture); a stochastic inference is receipt-verifiable, not reproducible (the receipt binds, Holo Q ADR-0052); the dual-trust proof is modelled with deterministic Ed25519, standing in for the chain's real sr25519 hotkey signature"
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#holo-bittensor-mcp",
        "dcterms:title": "Holo Bittensor (ADR-0071) is usable by AI agents over MCP — bittensor_snapshot · bittensor_agentfacts · bittensor_infer · bittensor_settle are advertised, JSON-Schema'd tools on the canonical Hologram MCP server (tools/list + /.well-known/mcp.json), each returning a SELF-VERIFYING UOR object the agent re-derives (Law L5): an agent maps a subnet's metagraph (a κ-rooted dcat:Catalog pinning the block hash), reads a neuron's dual-trust AgentFacts (NANDA record ⊕ UOR object ⊕ hotkey-signed VC), queries a miner and re-derives the PROV-O inference receipt, and settles TAO against PROVEN work (testnet-gated, tampered work pays nothing) — without trusting any server, and a tampered object is refused through the agent's own verify_object tool. The supply side of the agent economy, agent-callable."
      },
